<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-04-01T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-04-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="275" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d275">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/6127: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin (<persName type="from">Lockhart</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-04-01T13:00:00+08:00">April 1, 1933—1
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 1—4:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Telegraphic reports from two reliable sources Chinwangtao state that
                            Japanese occupied Hsimenchai this morning, short distance north <pb facs="0368" n="266" xml:id="pg_266"/> of Chinwangtao and well inside
                            the Wall. The situation in region of Shanhaikwan is becoming more tense,
                            considerable fighting west and northwest that place having occurred.
                            Japanese planes have been engaged in reconnoitring that region for
                            several days and in some instances dropping bombs.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>